\subsection{Governing 4D Dynamical System}
\label{subsec:governing_system}

We model the non-equilibrium thermodynamic and mechanical state of the nocturnal stable boundary layer (SBL) using a coupled four-dimensional system of ordinary differential equations (ODEs). The state vector is defined as $\mathbf{x} = (e, U, V, T_s)^T \in \mathcal{X}$, representing the turbulent kinetic energy (TKE) density, horizontal wind components, and land surface skin temperature respectively.

The governing system is given by:
\begin{align}
\varepsilon \frac{de}{dt} &= l_0\left[\eta \gamma (U^2 + V^2) - K G(T_s)\right] \sqrt{e + \delta} - (e + \delta) \label{eq:fast_tke} \\
\frac{dU}{dt} &= f(V - V_g) - \gamma \sqrt{e + \delta} \, U \label{eq:slow_u} \\
\frac{dV}{dt} &= -f(U - U_g) - \gamma \sqrt{e + \delta} \, V \label{eq:slow_v} \\
\frac{dT_s}{dt} &= \frac{1}{C_s} \left[ R_{\downarrow} - \sigma T_s^4 - \rho c_p C_H \sqrt{e + \delta} (T_s - T_a) - \frac{K_g}{d_g} (T_s - T_g) \right] \label{eq:slow_ts}
\end{align}

where the parameters and physical terms are defined as follows:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Turbulent Transport Mechanics:} Equation~\eqref{eq:fast_tke} balances shear production (driven by mechanical wind shear with efficiency $\eta$ and drag coefficient $\gamma$), buoyant destruction (moderated by the thermal stratification function $G(T_s)$ and conduction coefficient $K$), and viscous dissipation parameterized by the turbulent master length scale $l_0$.
    \item \textbf{Coriolis and Drag Coupling:} Equations~\eqref{eq:slow_u} and \eqref{eq:slow_v} couple horizontal momentum to geostrophic wind forcing $(U_g, V_g)$ and the Earth's rotation via the Coriolis parameter $f$, damped by turbulent drag proportional to the active root-TKE field $\sqrt{e+\delta}$.
    \item \textbf{Surface Energy Balance:} Equation~\eqref{eq:slow_ts} evolves the skin temperature $T_s$ on a slab with thermal capacity $C_s$, balancing incoming longwave radiation $R_{\downarrow}$, outgoing Stefan-Boltzmann radiative cooling $\sigma T_s^4$, sensible heat flux exchange with the near-surface air $T_a$, and conductive soil heat flux to a deep soil layer at temperature $T_g$.
\end{itemize}

The parameter $\delta > 0$ serves as a mathematical regularizer representing the background residual molecular dissipation, ensuring that the turbulent exchange coefficients do not collapse to absolute zero during completely laminar regimes.